<TITLE> Bourses back in the red </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Apr 7 (bdnews24.com)The bourses went back to losses on Tuesday after witnessing a rise the previous day propelled by bank shares. The Dhaka Stock Exchange's benchmark general index rose 39 points Monday while the selective category index of the Chittagong bourse surged almost 152 points. Despite the fall in indices, gaining scrips dominated Tuesday's trading. But losses in blue chip shares on the twin bourses also dented the market. Post-dividend trade and price adjustment of United Insurance and Lanka Bangla Finance also had an impact on the DSE indices. DSE general index fell sharply on the first hour of trading Tuesday but recovered losses on the second hour followed by a downward trend afterwards. The DGEN or general index fell 27.71 points or 1.12 percent, closing on 2438.44. The DSI or all share price index ended on 2024.36, down 20.77 points or 1.01 percent. The blue-chip DSE-20 lost 37.98 points or 1.98 percent to finish on 1872.35. Gainers beat losers 133 to 99 while six issues held steady. Indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange ended downbeat due to losses in the shares of banks, non-banking financial institutions and leather shares. The CSCX or selective categories index lost 63.87 points or 1.26 percent to close at 4975.25. The CASPI or all share price index ended on 7686.59, falling 93 points or 1.19 percent. The CSE-30 blue-chip index slumped 119.27 points or 2.07 percent to finish at 5635.79. Of the traded issues, 77 advanced, 74 declined with seven scrips unchanged. Brokerage house officials said banks that account for about 52 percent of the market capitalisation fell Tuesday on lower demand. "Although banks rose yesterday [Monday] investors especially the retail investors were reluctant to bet on them," an official of Latif Securities told bdnews24.com. He added that institutional investors had mainly opted Monday for banks Power and energy shares went up Tuesday while mutual funds ended mixed, said the brokerage house official asking not to be named. Meanwhile, trading volume fell from the previous day's. Dhaka Stock Exchange saw 23,889,635 shares worth Tk 4.35 billion changing hands, edging down from Monday's Tk 4.52 billion. Turnover on the port city's bourse reached Tk 685.190 million from trading of 4,794,866 sharesup from Tk 578.43 million the previous day. AIMS 1st mutual fund was the turnover leader on the CSE, with transactions of Tk 0.795 million followed by Shinepukur Ceramics, Padma Cement, Bextex Ltd and BHL. DSE's top ten by turnover Summit Power continued to top the board with a turnover of Tk 413.820 million. It rose 6.22 percent to Tk 1225.25. Beximco followed, with turnover of Tk 389.625 million, to end 4.87 percent up at Tk 245.10. Power Grid Company of Bangladesh ended on Tk 653.50, gaining 5.74 percent. It saw shares worth Tk 218.727 million changing hands. DESCO had shares worth Tk 205.788 million traded and gained 6.54 percent to end on Tk 1294.25. S Alam Cold Rolled Steels lost 2.55 percent to Tk 714.75 with a turnover of Tk 168.491 million. Among the other scrips on the turnover board Aftab Automibiles, Eastern Housing Ltd and Beximco Pharmaceuticalsrose on buying pressure. Summit Alliance Port Ltd and BSRM Steels fell on profit taking.
